## Python Deployment Servers & Frameworks

This is the direct equivalent of your Tomcat / Spring Boot question:

### WSGI Servers — traditional sync Python (equivalent of Tomcat)

| Server | Description | Best For |
|--------|-------------|----------|
| **Gunicorn** | Most widely used WSGI server, battle-tested | Flask, Django in production |
| **uWSGI** | High performance, more config-heavy | High-traffic Django apps |
| **Waitress** | Pure Python, Windows-friendly | Simple deployments |

### ASGI Servers — modern async Python (the current standard)

| Server | Description | Best For |
|--------|-------------|----------|
| **Uvicorn** | Fastest, built on uvloop | FastAPI, Starlette |
| **Hypercorn** | Supports HTTP/2 & HTTP/3 | Advanced async apps |
| **Daphne** | Django Channels' official server | Django with WebSockets |

### Web Frameworks — equivalent of Spring Boot

| Framework | Philosophy | Equivalent |
|-----------|------------|------------|
| **FastAPI** | Modern, async-first, auto OpenAPI docs | Spring Boot (most similar feel) |
| **Django** | Batteries-included, ORM, admin panel | Spring MVC + JPA + everything |
| **Flask** | Lightweight, minimal, flexible | Spring without the opinions |
| **Litestar** | High-performance alternative to FastAPI | Spring WebFlux |

